    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Administering an insulin correction bolus right after a meal can indeed supplement your meal insulin (also known as bolus), but considering your concerns about potential hypoglycemia, it might be better to err on the side of caution. Here's what you could consider:\n- Taking half of the correction dose and checking your blood sugar 30 minutes later. If it's still rising, you may need to take the other half.\n- You could also delay administering the bolus until after you've had the effect of your mealtime insulin and your blood sugar is more likely to stay stable.\n- Consider the overall impact of the meal, your current blood sugar, and your typical insulin sensitivity in the post-meal period.\n\nSince the concept of the 'rule of 15' is to give a 15g carbohydrate snack if your blood sugar drops below 70 mg/dL, think of how your blood sugar will fluctuate. Be mindful of potential hypoglycemia and always follow a cautious approach when consuming insulin. Ultimately, discuss your meal timing and any adjustment to your insulin regimen with your healthcare provider for safe and personalized advice.",
